Neither `target` nor `currentTarget` refers to the element targeted by the selector passed to `atom.contextMenu.add` if the event originated on a descendant of that element and the event bubbled to it. Since the context menu checking appears to delegate from an event listener on the document, `delegateTarget` is `document` and isn't useful.

The `created` callback should be called when the click event reaches the element matching the selector because `currentTarget` will match the element at that point.

**DOM:**

``` html
<div class="foo">
  <div class="bar" style="height: 20px; width: 20px;">
  </div>
</div>
```

**JS:**

``` js
atom.contextMenu.add({
  '.foo': {
    created: (event) {
      // `event.target` === `<div class="bar">`
      // `event.currentTarget` === `event.delegateTarget` === `document`
      //
      // How can the `<div class="foo">` element be referenced?
    },
  },
});
```
